  "text": "Note that the algorithms for solving k-anonymity aim at finding a k-minimal table, that is, one that does not generalize (or suppress) more than it is needed to reach the threshold k. As an example, consider the microdata table in Figure 1.2(a) and suppose that the quasi-identifier is {Race, Date of birth, Sex, ZIP}. Figure 1 .4 illustrates an example of 2-anonymous table obtained by applying the algorithm described in [CITATION_1] , where generalization is applied at the column level and suppression is applied at the row level. Note that the first tuple in the original table has been suppressed and attribute Date of birth has been generalized by removing the day and attribute ZIP has been generalized by applying two generalization steps along the domain generalization hierarchy in Figure 1 .3.",
